16 2021-04-07 disorientation Asthma Attack started at 1 pm while seated and attending virtual class. She was under no distress an... Read more
Close
Asthma Attack started at 1 pm while seated and attending virtual class. She was under no distress and was not in any way exerting herself. She described the attack as a feeling of someone sitting on her chest and began to hyperventilate. The color drained from her face and her hands felt numb. Her asthma attacks are generally exercise-induced, so this was highly unusual. She took a dose of albuterol ( 2 puffs with a spacer) and followed her asthma action plan. She laid down and slowed her breathing. 20 minutes later her facial color returned to normal. Two hours later her hands returned to normal. She was disoriented for about 5 hours.

Close
Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance after consent was acquired. At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store. at 1807, Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse. The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury. EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor. The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS. EMS exited the building at 1827. The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer. Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.

Patient received vaccine around 4:30pm. After 10 minutes patient reported that she was having a headache, felt like her breathing was a little bit heavy. Patient was brought to exam room with mother present. BP was 150s/100, O2: 99%, HR: 65, RR 20. No distress noted. Patient was slightly anxious, continued to complain about headache. Denied any blurred vision, changes in vision, nausea, vomiting. Around 4:45, patient was asked to lay down for a while to be observed further and to give her time to relax. Patient was given cold wash cloths for forehead. Patient suddenly became more increasing anxious at 4:49, complained of excruciating headache and bilateral arm pain. Oxygen remained at 100%. 911 called at 4:50pm. Paramedics arrived at 4:55pm. Paramedics checked patient's blood sugar: approximately 345. Patient reported last meal around 12:30pm. Patient was crying and continually stating that her head hurt. She was alert throughout the entire process and able to answer questions. Mother elected to have patient sent to ER for further evaluation. Followed up with family on 04/14/2021. Mother reported that patient was held at hospital for 5 hours, was given norco for headache. Diagnosed with panic attack. Mother reports that patient is doing better today.

16 2021-04-22 sensation of foreign body Pt. received her second Pfizer dose at 3pm. By 11:30pm she had significant swelling on both of her e... Read more
Close
Pt. received her second Pfizer dose at 3pm. By 11:30pm she had significant swelling on both of her eyes, mouth, and the start of red splotchy skin on arms and legs. We took her to ER. They gave her 50mg of hydroxizine and sent us home. 5min after leaving the ER at 12:30am on 4/23 she felt a golf ball sized lump in her throat and was having difficulty breathing. We brought her back to the ER. At this time they gave her an ekg, and at around 1:30am gave her an epi pin and an oral steroid. Within 5min of the oral steroid and epi pin she no longer had difficulty in breathing and the lump in her throat was gone as was the res splotches. By 5am the swelling in her face had reduced drastically to 90% normal in her left eye and 70% normal in her right eye and 70% normal in her lip. She was released from the ER at 5:45am and went home to sleep. At 11:30am on 4/23 her swelling in her face remains the same and she is complaining of a headache. She was given 50mg more of hydroxizine.

I got the shot at around 4 in the afternoon and after sitting in the waiting area for around 15 minutes I was allowed to leave. When I left I only had a slight headache, but nothing that seemed very noticeable. I felt a tad woozy but it was nothing serious so I went on with my day and went to my sports practice for an hour and a half. After I got home and had eaten, I was working and started to feel the effects. It started with an increasingly worse headache at around 9 and as the night went on it got worse and I constantly needed to lie down. My arm had started to feel sore but it was nothing much. I thought I could sleep it off but woke up feeling horrible. My stomach could not hold any food down and my headache had become really bad. I had to go to my sports game but on the car ride over (around 45 min) I got very nauseous. Throughout the course of the day my headache would get worse any time I tried to run and all I wanted to do was lie down and sleep. I was barely able to stand, let alone run and I felt sleepy all day. My arm had also gotten very sore and any contact on it made me flinch back. I was not able to eat or drink anything until about 4 in the afternoon and my stomach was not sitting right the entire time and I constantly was burping and feeling like I was going to vomit despite having only water in my stomach. After I was able to eat the stomach ache went away a bit but the headache lasted through the night and has finally started to subside two days later.

16 2021-04-25 crying An hour after Pfizer vaccine administration, the parents of the 16 year old patient returned to the ... Read more
Close
An hour after Pfizer vaccine administration, the parents of the 16 year old patient returned to the pharmacy and reported that their daughter was complaining of trouble breathing in the parking lot. The immunizing tech asked the parents to bring the patient back to the pharmacy. The patient returned and while crying and gasping for air, she reported that it felt as if someone was constricting her throat. She also complained of stiff fingers and feeling numbness/tingling in her upper extremities. Assuming anaphylactic reaction, one dose of epinephrine was administered. The patient said she felt slightly better after the first dose but then 2 minutes later, said her breathing was getting worse, and again described feeling her throat tightening. Five minutes later, a 2nd dose of epinephrine was administered. The patient was taken to the hospital by paramedics.

Patient was vaccinated and left with her mother to sit in her car for 30 minute monitoring period. Patient's mother stated patient was experiencing extreme anxiety getting the vaccine and after 20 minutes was wheezing. She brought patient inside and a Pharmacist came to check on her and her mother stated that she has had a reaction to a medication in the past and just needed Benadryl. Benadryl was given to her and she took it orally. Her pulse and blood oxygen were measured with a finger pulse oximeter and were both normal. Shortly after she was panicking more and had a seizure. Her mother reported that she has frequent seizures when she has anxiety/panic episodes. Her seizures were persisting so 911 was called. Paramedics arrived shortly after and took patient to the hospital. A few hours later the patient's mother came back to us to inform us that she was released from the hospital and was feeling fine and back to normal.

16 2021-05-03 anxiety Patient reported feeling lightheaded status post first dose Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot: EW0167, expir... Read more
Close
Patient reported feeling lightheaded status post first dose Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot: EW0167, expiration date: 08/31/2021) to medic. Medic noted that the client was CAOx4, her skin was pale, warm and slightly moist, pupils were equal, round, reactive to light and accommodating (PEARRL), respiration rate (RR) was 20. The client's sister stated the client had a history of anxiety and that "she gets this way whenever she gets a shot". Medic walked patient to the zero gravity chair. The client was given water to sip on. At 1213 baseline vitals were taken with client sitting: Blood pressure (BP): 110/82, heartrate (HR): 98, RR: 20, PEARRL. Medic reports she coached the client on her breathing to help alleviate her complaint of feeling lightheaded, mild nausea and anxiety. Client reported she felt anxious prior to her vaccination and that her last oral intake was 15 minutes prior to vaccine. Client denied headache, blurry vision and chest pain. At 1220 a second set of vitals were taken while standing: BP 108/80, HR 86, RR 16, CAOx4. Client stated her symptoms were diminishing. Client's RR slowed down to normal rate and rhythm, vital signs were trending to normal and client was negative for orthostatic pressures. Client was advised to stay for additional 30 minute observation. 16 2021-05-06 amnesia My 16-year-old daughter, very healthy without any health conditions, got her first dose of the Pfize... Read more
Close
My 16-year-old daughter, very healthy without any health conditions, got her first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Saturday evening, April 10th, at around 5pm. On Wednesday, she started complaining of shortness of breath, chest pains, which she described as a feeling of someone stubbing her heart. By Thursday, she began blacking out repeatedly throughout the day, each blackout lasting about a minute. These progressed and whenever she blacked out, she would not remember what happened. At first, she and I brushed it off as maybe lack of calcium since she rarely drinks milk. But as they intensified, I began to become more concerned. I told her I cannot leave her by herself in the house as I prepared to go pick up her young siblings from school then schedule an appointment with her doctor. On our way back home, she blacked out again, however, it was for more than a minute. Straight away, I drove to the ER close by. The doctor came back to inform me that her heartbeat was irregular and concerning based on her age. In that same moment, she began complaining of excessive pain like someone punching her heart out, and then she passed out again. Still with my two other children, the whole ordeal began to frighten them and illicit some heavy tears. Being that this ER was general admission, the doctors insisted they call in the paramedics to transport her to another ER for children. However, after being transported to the other ER, her condition began to intensify rather quickly and the pediatric doctor at the second ER informed us we would have to be transferred to Childrens intensive care unit where the cardiologists could check her heart, find the ultimate cause, and monitor her closely. In that moment, as a mother, I was speechless and extremely terrified. Seeing my daughter being transferred from ER to ER, made it even tougher on me so much that I could no longer hold myself together. Here she was in terrible pain and being moved around with no clear diagnosis and treatment. From there on, we spent a couple days in the Cardiac ICU waiting and praying with friends for answers and the best treatment she could get to ease the pain. By about the third day of being in the ICU, the cardiologists informed me, she had Acute Myocarditis. This was so shocking in a sense that both sides of the family have no history of heart issues. Secondly, she is a very healthy child.

At 2am 4/22 patient started to feel sick and sent a text that I didn't read until 630 as I was asleep. She woke up around 10:45 and was feeling decent except for a headache but no fever or anything so we went to try on some Prom dresses. I scooped her up, brought her to the ER where they ran every test and scan imagineable. Full blood work up and cultures, a chest xray, a CT scan of her brain and lungs. She also had IV Tordahl for the headache. Her inflammatory markers were high at 15.3 which we were told should be less than 1. They reran labs in the morning but everything can back really low which they felt was a dilution effect from all the fluids so wanted us to follow up with her primary care on Monday. On Saturday night, he lymph nodes were swollen to the size of ping pong balls but have since slowly reduced in size although still there. Her labs were better from discharge and her white blood cell count was within range and her inflammatory marker was down to 1.7. Her blood sugar was a little low. She did pass out and have seizure like response to giving blood in the doctors office, lost bladder control again, shot pupils, etc. She is still stuttering over words, has some short term memory retention and has some motor function issues which they think is a result of the initial seizure and should resolve itself over time. Her liver function tests were totally normal in the hospital but are a high now so they will be checking her out again next week.

Recipient is a 17yo who presented for second dose of COVID-19 vaccine. She reported some anxiety related to receiving dose #2, and had some nausea after dose #1. She was alone as a driver of her own POV. Consent was obtained from the recipient and her custodial grandparent by phone, witnessed by doctor. She initially did well after the vaccine, but after approximately 5 minutes began to complain of feeling nauseated, lightheaded, and tingling extremities (hands and feet). She was noted to be hyperventilating, and was placed in a supine position but continued to feel some lightheadedness and difficulty breathing. Breath sounds were clear without wheezing noted, HR 70s with RRR. She was noted to have ongoing anxiety, nausea and symptoms progressed and although she remained normotensive to hypertensive (initial BP 128/74), she had repeated episodes of syncope. She was transferred to the ambulance and further vitals and EKG were obtained. She had some confusion after episodes of syncope and some seizure-like activity with syncope, with very brief episodes of LOC, with noted tachycardia with HR up to the 140s during episodes of syncope. BP ranged 129/86 to 140/84. IV access obtained and she was given NS and started on oxygen at 2 liters, but saturations remained in the 98-99% range. She was ultimately transferred to the local ER for further evaluation and management given ongoing symptoms, evaluated at hospital.

Information about lot/batch number was requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available and temporal association, a possible causal relationship cannot be excluded between the suspect product BNT162B2 and the reported event Passed out. The client appeared drowsy but was oriented to person and place. The client?s eyelids were open halfway, and the client was mumbling answers to the questions. The client stated, ?I feel dizzy and hot under my skin.? Vital signs were taken by EMT at 1901 (Heart rate 92, Oxygen 99%, blood pressure 112/P?client was wearing a long-sleeved shirt). Client?s skin was warm and dry. At 1902 client appeared more alert, and PHN gave the client juice to drink, which she accepted and drank. Client stated that she has a history of vasal vagal reactions to needles and was anxious about receiving today?s vaccine. EMT and PHN transitioned client to zero gravity chair at 1904 and gave client chips and a granola bar to eat. The client accepted the snacks and started to eat them. At 1905 client stated, ?my head feels weird like I want to lay back.? PHN advised client to lay her head back onto the gravity chair head rest. Client laid her head back for less than 30 seconds than continued to eat. PHN offered the client Benadryl and she refused. Client stated that the last time that she ate was around 1100 or 1200. Client was wearing a beanie and long sleeves, we asked the client if she can remove her hat and outer layer, however, she refused. The client had a flat affect and was soft spoken. Vital signs taken at 1915 (oxygen 98%, heart rate 94, blood pressure 138/84). Client denied any shortness of breath. At 1919, client stated, ?I feel like I?m going to throw up.? The zero-gravity chair was positioned into a seating position and the client was given an emesis bag. Client did not vomit, and she sat with the emesis bag until 1923 and then stated that the feeling was gone. Client has a history of sickle cell anemia and stated that she receives blood transfusions every 2-3 weeks but had not received a transfusion in 8 weeks. Client is currently prescribed Metformin but has not taken the medication because ?she does not trust it.? Client stated that she was prescribed Lexapro 1 month ago and took her first dose the day before the vaccine but did not take it the day of the vaccine. She stated that she has anxiety but denied any other medical conditions. She is allergic to Toradol. Vital signs taken at 1924 (oxygen 98%, heart rate 91, blood pressure 146/102). At 1925 she sated ?my head hurts, it?s a sharp pain.? PHN called EMS at 1926. EMS arrived at 1928 and assumed care. EMS medic stated that her blood glucose levels were at 82 and advised her that they wanted to take her to the emergency room to be examined. The client refused transport to the hospital and stated, ?I don?t want to go to the hospital, it?s so expensive.? Client continued to refuse transport and stated that she will have her boyfriend take her to the hospital. Client?s boyfriend entered the building and client signed an AMA at 1953. PHN provided education to client and boyfriend on life threatening symptoms and to call EMS if any symptoms appear on their way to the hospital. PHN also advised client to follow up with her primary care provider and to follow up with an allergist before receiving her second vaccine. Client left the facility AMA at 1954 with her boyfriend, unassisted and with a steady gait. Client and her boyfriend stated that they would go to the hospital.

19 2021-07-13 anxiety, sleep disorder 1. My period, which I got on April 20th (18 days after dose 2), resulted in extreme and debilitating... Read more
Close
1. My period, which I got on April 20th (18 days after dose 2), resulted in extreme and debilitating cramps, which are lasting to this day. They're so bad I can't get out of bed for the first two days of my period - then I have infrequent occasional pangs of pain on day 3, and I'm okay days 4 and 5. I have never had cramps during my cycle before April 2021. 2. On April 16th, I was driving my car and I noticed that when I had my foot on the the brake, it was shaking uncontrollably in almost every position I put my leg in. The frequency of this leg tremor during driving became more frequent, and I started noticing heightened anxiety, trouble focusing, weight loss of 7 pounds thus far (my weight has not fluctuated more then 3 pounds in the last 4 years so this was a surprise to me), lightened period, increased heat intolerance, heart palpitations that keep me awake at night and tachychardia, muscle weakness, and fatigue. I had a really stressful semester in school so I chalked these symptoms up to anxiety. Then, in the first week of June, I went to the gynecologist to get the cramps situation checked out. She told me she wanted me to check out my thyroid for the rest of the symptoms. When my blood test came back, my Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH) result came back as 0.03 (lowest acceptable range is 0.4). My primary care provider ran T3 and T4 tests, which came back as 15 and 5, respectively - which are both quite elevated for their range. So, I went to an endocrinologist at my primary care provider's referral, who ran more tests. This time, they found TSH to be 0.006 (got lower), T3 and T4 were elevated, very slightly lower than they were before. My endocrinologist then ran a test for Thyroglobulin antibody, which came back as 53.3, when the highest reference value was 0.9. Thus, my endocrinologist determined hyperthyroidism, but wanted to figure out the what I had so she sent me for a thyroid uptake scan. In the scan, they found my thyroid to be working at 51%, when the highest value after 24 hours of receiving the radioactive iodine was 33%, and my endocrinologist determined that I had Graves' Disease, an autoimmune hyperthyroid disease. I am now on Methimazole and Propranolol for Graves' Disease. I don't know if the vaccine caused my horrendously painful cramps and the onset of the autoimmune disease, but I just wanted the CDC to know! I am curious to know if there is a correlation. Please let me know if you have any questions.

On both my first and second shot I got really bad brain fog. I went to the ER after my first shot on June 29, 2021 but they told me it was a psychological thing and that I was freaking myself out and that it was not vaccine related but I knew the at wasn?t the case. After my first shot the pressure in my head remained for about a week and the brain fog and vision/auditory issues only occurred on the first day mainly. On my second shot today (07/20/2021) it occurred again and so I know it?s vaccine related, not psychological. On both shots it was an immediate reaction. As soon as the person began to inject the vaccine into me I would feel immediate pressure in my head (on the first shot it felt like the vaccine literally traveled to my fingertips in my left arm and up into my head, it was very strange). Then about 2-5 minutes after I got the vaccine on both occasions my vision became filled with floaters and my coherency decreased. The first vaccine was the worst as the floaters stayed longer and my vision would go in and out of bluriness more. On the second shot the floaters were very obvious for the first hour and then slowly decreased over time but it is currently 6 hours after my shot right now and I still see a couple. On my second shot my vision did blur but not as bad. Both times I felt tremendous pressure in my head and I couldn?t think straight or focus. My speech was very slow and the ordering of my words were inaccurate. My texting was bad because I couldn?t spell and the structure of my sentences was incorrect. I have issues putting words together to say what I want to say and I can?t concentrate. Both times I have stared at a wall in fixation for hours which is not normal. It?s not so much as a headache, just a lot of pressure and I?ve never experienced it with anything else in my life. After my second dose I was also extremely exhausted but could not sleep because of the pressure in my head. My memory is also affected as I cannot remember things very well. It takes me about 30 seconds to understand what someone says because I just can?t think. I feel like my cognitive processes are faulty. It?s like a very intense brain fog that affects my vision and on the first vaccine also affected my hearing as stuff sounded muffled.

I made sure to hydrate and eat well the day of the vaccine. I have had no allergic reactions to any medications/ injections in the past and I was not worried about this one. I felt clammy/sweaty and kept shifting my weight in my seat. I didn't want to make a big deal of it at first because I worried it was all in my head. But I became more and more uncomfortable. I laid my head down on the little desk, no help. I closed my eyes, no help. About 10 minutes or so in I decided to ask if they had water available. I slowly got up and walked to the back of the room. I couldn't even get the question out of my mouth before the nurse told me to sit down. Apparently I was white as a ghost. They got a wheelchair and wheeled me to the space behind the auditorium. They then put me in a wheelchair and wheeled me back into the lobby for some more time. Then, they wheeled me back to a room where they gave some lactated ringers and a PA and MD saw me. By then my BP and breathing was completely resolved. The MD said he wasn't fully convinced it was just a vasovagal episode because I haven't had issues with vaccines in the past and I was well hydrated and my HR was normal. It partly fit the picture for an allergic reaction/ severe immune response d/t the feeling of throat closing, the BP drop, and the elevated WBCs. They advised that I list the vaccine as an allergy and do not get the second dose, especially since I had COVID back in September.

Close
I'd had Bell's Palsy (BP) twice in my life (once in 2013 and once in 2015). I have not had it since 2015 until I got vaccinated on 3/29/21 and began to develop BP symptoms on the evening of 4/6/21 (headache on right side of my head/temple, odd sensation on right side of my tongue, almost like I burned it on a hot beverage) but I didn't think anything of it. I went to sleep and then, on the morning of 4/7/21, I woke up feeling extremely fatigued, brain fogged, and weak. I didn't notice any of the BP symptoms until I went to brush my teeth and realized I had lost motor function in the right side of my mouth. I immediately made a telehealth appointment with an Urgent Care doctor in order to get an Rx of Prednisone. I began taking the Prednisone around 3pm on Wednesday, 4/7/21. I also have been taking vitamin B-12 and a Women's Multivitamin to help regenerate nerve function. However, since starting the prednisone, my symptoms have continued to develop. Symptoms currently include: right side of my face is extremely swollen; I have lost mobility on the right side of my face, the right side of my tongue still feels numb; right eye tearing non-stop; some mild ear pain in right inner ear; slight pins-and-needles sensation in my fingers on my right hand; difficulty eating and drinking; still feeling fatigued. I have recovered from BP twice before so I am not too worried about having it again. I just think the FDA needs to put out a warning to the public that there may be a correlation between the COVID-19 mRNA vaccines and Bell's Palsy recurrences. I know this is not a coincidence, and my BP relapse was a result of my body experiencing an immune reaction from the vaccine.

The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19, prior to vaccination and has not been tested for COVID, since the vaccination. After second vaccine, she had no side effects until exactly 6 days after her second dose. On 30May2021 at 9:30 PM, patient experienced as her left arm started getting a sensation of pins and needles. Her heart then started to palpitate and she could feel her left chest muscle tensing up. She thought that she was having a heart attack, so her husband rushed her to the ER. While in the waiting room, she calmed down and realized it wasn't life threading. She also was experiencing extreme dizziness, light headedness, and fatigue. She never had dealt with this before until her vaccine. But it felt like she was dying. Her BP and heart rate were so elevated for a month. She went to her primary and was diagnosed with panic disorder. She went home and it happened again for an hour and she took magnesium and went to sleep. Seriousness as reported as No. On 30May2021, patient underwent lab test which included Blood pressure measurement and heart results increased. The outcome of all events was recovered with sequel/ Recovered with lasting effects. Follow-Up (15Jul2021): Follow-up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.
